Yes — that’s a good way to look at it, and biology actually supports a version of what you’re describing.

1. Epigenetics as a kind of biological memory

Epigenetics refers to chemical marks on DNA or on the proteins that package DNA that affect how genes are used without changing the underlying DNA sequence.

Examples include:
	•	DNA methylation
	•	histone modification
	•	chromatin structure changes

These marks can sometimes persist through cell divisions and occasionally across generations, which is why people sometimes call epigenetics a “memory of environmental experience.”

Important nuance:
Most epigenetic marks are reset each generation, but some signals can persist long enough to influence traits in descendants.

So the genome carries the long-term blueprint, while epigenetics can carry short-term adaptive memory layered on top.

